1 //===-- LICM.cpp - Loop Invariant Code Motion Pass ------------------------===// ----
2 // ----
3 // Part of the LLVM Project, under the Apache License v2.0 with LLVM Exceptions. ----
4 // See https://llvm.org/LICENSE.txt for license information. ----
5 // SPDX-License-Identifier: Apache-2.0 WITH LLVM-exception ----

7 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----
8 // ----
9 // This pass performs loop invariant code motion, attempting to remove as much ----
10 // code from the body of a loop as possible. It does this by either hoisting ----
11 // code into the preheader block, or by sinking code to the exit blocks if it is ----
12 // safe. This pass also promotes must-aliased memory locations in the loop to ----
13 // live in registers, thus hoisting and sinking "invariant" loads and stores. ----
14 // ----
15 // Hoisting operations out of loops is a canonicalization transform. It ----
16 // enables and simplifies subsequent optimizations in the middle-end. ----
17 // Rematerialization of hoisted instructions to reduce register pressure is the ----
18 // responsibility of the back-end, which has more accurate information about ----
19 // register pressure and also handles other optimizations than LICM that ----
20 // increase live-ranges. ----
21 // ----
22 // This pass uses alias analysis for two purposes: ----
23 // ----
24 // 1. Moving loop invariant loads and calls out of loops. If we can determine ----
25 // that a load or call inside of a loop never aliases anything stored to, ----
26 // we can hoist it or sink it like any other instruction. ----
27 // 2. Scalar Promotion of Memory - If there is a store instruction inside of ----
28 // the loop, we try to move the store to happen AFTER the loop instead of ----
29 // inside of the loop. This can only happen if a few conditions are true: ----
30 // A. The pointer stored through is loop invariant ----
31 // B. There are no stores or loads in the loop which _may_ alias the ----
32 // pointer. There are no calls in the loop which mod/ref the pointer. ----
33 // If these conditions are true, we can promote the loads and stores in the ----
34 // loop of the pointer to use a temporary alloca'd variable. We then use ----
35 // the SSAUpdater to construct the appropriate SSA form for the value. ----
36 // ----
37 //===----------------------------------------------------------------------===// ----

130 // Experimental option to allow imprecision in LICM in pathological cases, in ----
131 // exchange for faster compile. This is to be removed if MemorySSA starts to ----
132 // address the same issue. LICM calls MemorySSAWalker's ----
133 // getClobberingMemoryAccess, up to the value of the Cap, getting perfect ----
134 // accuracy. Afterwards, LICM will call into MemorySSA's getDefiningAccess, ----
135 // which may not be precise, since optimizeUses is capped. The result is ----
136 // correct, but we may not get as "far up" as possible to get which access is ----
137 // clobbering the one queried. ----
138 cl::opt llvm::SetLicmMssaOptCap( ----
139 "licm-mssa-optimization-cap", cl::init(100), cl::Hidden, ----
140 cl::desc("Enable imprecision in LICM in pathological cases, in exchange " ----
141 "for faster compile. Caps the MemorySSA clobbering calls.")); ----
142 ----
143 // Experimentally, memory promotion carries less importance than sinking and ----
144 // hoisting. Limit when we do promotion when using MemorySSA, in order to save ----
145 // compile time. ----

147 "licm-mssa-max-acc-promotion", cl::init(250), cl::Hidden, ----

149 "effect. When MSSA in LICM is enabled, then this is the maximum " ----
150 "number of accesses allowed to be present in a loop in order to " ----
151 "enable memory promotion.")); ----

388 /// Hoist expressions out of the specified loop. Note, alias info for inner ----
389 /// loop is not preserved so it is not a good idea to run LICM multiple ----
390 /// times on one loop. ----
391 bool LoopInvariantCodeMotion::runOnLoop(Loop *L, AAResults *AA, LoopInfo *LI, 0
392 DominatorTree *DT, AssumptionCache *AC, ----
393 TargetLibraryInfo *TLI, ----
394 TargetTransformInfo *TTI, ----
395 ScalarEvolution *SE, MemorySSA *MSSA, ----
396 OptimizationRemarkEmitter *ORE, ----
397 bool LoopNestMode) { ----
398 bool Changed = false; 0
399 ----
400 assert(L->isLCSSAForm(*DT) && "Loop is not in LCSSA form."); 0
401 ----
402 // If this loop has metadata indicating that LICM is not to be performed then ----
403 // just exit. ----
404 if (hasDisableLICMTransformsHint(L)) { 0
405 return false; 0
406 } ----
407 ----
408 // Don't sink stores from loops with coroutine suspend instructions. ----
409 // LICM would sink instructions into the default destination of ----
410 // the coroutine switch. The default destination of the switch is to ----
411 // handle the case where the coroutine is suspended, by which point the ----
412 // coroutine frame may have been destroyed. No instruction can be sunk there. ----
413 // FIXME: This would unfortunately hurt the performance of coroutines, however ----
414 // there is currently no general solution for this. Similar issues could also ----
415 // potentially happen in other passes where instructions are being moved ----
416 // across that edge. ----
417 bool HasCoroSuspendInst = llvm::any_of(L->getBlocks(), [](BasicBlock *BB) { 0
418 return llvm::any_of(*BB, [](Instruction &I) { 0
419 IntrinsicInst *II = dyn_cast(&I); 0
420 return II && II->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::coro_suspend; 0
421 }); 0
422 }); ----
423 ----
424 MemorySSAUpdater MSSAU(MSSA); 0
425 SinkAndHoistLICMFlags Flags(LicmMssaOptCap, LicmMssaNoAccForPromotionCap, ----
426 /*IsSink=*/true, *L, *MSSA); 0
427 ----
428 // Get the preheader block to move instructions into... ----
429 BasicBlock *Preheader = L->getLoopPreheader(); 0
430 ----
431 // Compute loop safety information. ----
432 ICFLoopSafetyInfo SafetyInfo; 0
433 SafetyInfo.computeLoopSafetyInfo(L); 0
434 ----
435 // We want to visit all of the instructions in this loop... that are not parts ----
436 // of our subloops (they have already had their invariants hoisted out of ----
437 // their loop, into this loop, so there is no need to process the BODIES of ----
438 // the subloops). ----
439 // ----
440 // Traverse the body of the loop in depth first order on the dominator tree so ----
441 // that we are guaranteed to see definitions before we see uses. This allows ----
442 // us to sink instructions in one pass, without iteration. After sinking ----
443 // instructions, we perform another pass to hoist them out of the loop. ----
444 if (L->hasDedicatedExits()) 0
445 Changed |= 0
446 LoopNestMode ----
447 ? sinkRegionForLoopNest(DT->getNode(L->getHeader()), AA, LI, DT, 0
448 TLI, TTI, L, MSSAU, &SafetyInfo, Flags, ORE) ----
449 : sinkRegion(DT->getNode(L->getHeader()), AA, LI, DT, TLI, TTI, L, 0
450 MSSAU, &SafetyInfo, Flags, ORE); ----
451 Flags.setIsSink(false); 0
452 if (Preheader) 0
453 Changed |= hoistRegion(DT->getNode(L->getHeader()), AA, LI, DT, AC, TLI, L, 0
454 MSSAU, SE, &SafetyInfo, Flags, ORE, LoopNestMode, ----
455 LicmAllowSpeculation); 0
456 ----
457 // Now that all loop invariants have been removed from the loop, promote any ----
458 // memory references to scalars that we can. ----
459 // Don't sink stores from loops without dedicated block exits. Exits ----
460 // containing indirect branches are not transformed by loop simplify, ----
461 // make sure we catch that. An additional load may be generated in the ----
462 // preheader for SSA updater, so also avoid sinking when no preheader ----
463 // is available. ----
464 if (!DisablePromotion && Preheader && L->hasDedicatedExits() && 0
465 !Flags.tooManyMemoryAccesses() && !HasCoroSuspendInst) { 0
466 // Figure out the loop exits and their insertion points ----
467 SmallVector ExitBlocks; 0
468 L->getUniqueExitBlocks(ExitBlocks); 0
469 ----
470 // We can't insert into a catchswitch. ----
471 bool HasCatchSwitch = llvm::any_of(ExitBlocks, [](BasicBlock *Exit) { 0
472 return isa(Exit->getTerminator()); 0
473 }); ----
474 ----
475 if (!HasCatchSwitch) { 0
476 SmallVector InsertPts; 0
477 SmallVector MSSAInsertPts; 0
478 InsertPts.reserve(ExitBlocks.size()); 0
479 MSSAInsertPts.reserve(ExitBlocks.size()); 0
480 for (BasicBlock *ExitBlock : ExitBlocks) { 0
481 InsertPts.push_back(&*ExitBlock->getFirstInsertionPt()); 0
482 MSSAInsertPts.push_back(nullptr); 0
483 } ----
484 ----
485 PredIteratorCache PIC; 0
486 ----
487 // Promoting one set of accesses may make the pointers for another set ----
488 // loop invariant, so run this in a loop. ----
489 bool Promoted = false; 0
490 bool LocalPromoted; ----
491 do { 0
492 LocalPromoted = false; 0
493 for (auto [PointerMustAliases, HasReadsOutsideSet] : 0
494 collectPromotionCandidates(MSSA, AA, L)) { 0
495 LocalPromoted |= promoteLoopAccessesToScalars( 0
496 PointerMustAliases, ExitBlocks, InsertPts, MSSAInsertPts, PIC, LI, ----
497 DT, AC, TLI, TTI, L, MSSAU, &SafetyInfo, ORE, ----
498 LicmAllowSpeculation, HasReadsOutsideSet); 0
499 } 0
500 Promoted |= LocalPromoted; 0
501 } while (LocalPromoted); ----
502 ----
503 // Once we have promoted values across the loop body we have to ----
504 // recursively reform LCSSA as any nested loop may now have values defined ----
505 // within the loop used in the outer loop. ----
506 // FIXME: This is really heavy handed. It would be a bit better to use an ----
507 // SSAUpdater strategy during promotion that was LCSSA aware and reformed ----
508 // it as it went. ----
509 if (Promoted) 0
510 formLCSSARecursively(*L, *DT, LI, SE); 0
511 ----
512 Changed |= Promoted; 0
513 } 0
514 } 0
515 ----
516 // Check that neither this loop nor its parent have had LCSSA broken. LICM is ----
517 // specifically moving instructions across the loop boundary and so it is ----
518 // especially in need of basic functional correctness checking here. ----
519 assert(L->isLCSSAForm(*DT) && "Loop not left in LCSSA form after LICM!"); 0
520 assert((L->isOutermost() || L->getParentLoop()->isLCSSAForm(*DT)) && 0
521 "Parent loop not left in LCSSA form after LICM!"); ----
522 ----
523 if (VerifyMemorySSA) 0
524 MSSA->verifyMemorySSA(); 0
525 ----
526 if (Changed && SE) 0
527 SE->forgetLoopDispositions(); 0
528 return Changed; 0
529 } 0
530 ----
531 /// Walk the specified region of the CFG (defined by all blocks dominated by ----
532 /// the specified block, and that are in the current loop) in reverse depth ----
533 /// first order w.r.t the DominatorTree. This allows us to visit uses before ----
534 /// definitions, allowing us to sink a loop body in one pass without iteration. ----
535 /// ----
536 bool llvm::sinkRegion(DomTreeNode *N, AAResults *AA, LoopInfo *LI, 0
537 DominatorTree *DT, TargetLibraryInfo *TLI, ----
538 TargetTransformInfo *TTI, Loop *CurLoop, ----
539 MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU, ICFLoopSafetyInfo *SafetyInfo, ----
540 SinkAndHoistLICMFlags &Flags, ----
541 OptimizationRemarkEmitter *ORE, Loop *OutermostLoop) { ----
542 ----
543 // Verify inputs. ----
544 assert(N != nullptr && AA != nullptr && LI != nullptr && DT != nullptr && 0
545 CurLoop != nullptr && SafetyInfo != nullptr && ----
546 "Unexpected input to sinkRegion."); ----
547 ----
548 // We want to visit children before parents. We will enqueue all the parents ----
549 // before their children in the worklist and process the worklist in reverse ----
550 // order. ----
551 SmallVector Worklist = collectChildrenInLoop(N, CurLoop); 0
552 ----
553 bool Changed = false; 0
554 for (DomTreeNode *DTN : reverse(Worklist)) { 0
555 BasicBlock *BB = DTN->getBlock(); 0
556 // Only need to process the contents of this block if it is not part of a ----
557 // subloop (which would already have been processed). ----
558 if (inSubLoop(BB, CurLoop, LI)) 0
559 continue; 0
560 ----
561 for (BasicBlock::iterator II = BB->end(); II != BB->begin();) { 0
562 Instruction &I = *--II; 0
563 ----
564 // The instruction is not used in the loop if it is dead. In this case, ----
565 // we just delete it instead of sinking it. ----
566 if (isInstructionTriviallyDead(&I, TLI)) { 0
567 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "LICM deleting dead inst: " << I << '\n'); 0
568 salvageKnowledge(&I); 0
569 salvageDebugInfo(I); 0
570 ++II; 0
571 eraseInstruction(I, *SafetyInfo, MSSAU); 0
572 Changed = true; 0
573 continue; 0
574 } ----
575 ----
576 // Check to see if we can sink this instruction to the exit blocks ----
577 // of the loop. We can do this if the all users of the instruction are ----
578 // outside of the loop. In this case, it doesn't even matter if the ----
579 // operands of the instruction are loop invariant. ----
580 // ----
581 bool FoldableInLoop = false; 0
582 bool LoopNestMode = OutermostLoop != nullptr; 0
583 if (!I.mayHaveSideEffects() && 0
584 isNotUsedOrFoldableInLoop(I, LoopNestMode ? OutermostLoop : CurLoop, 0
585 SafetyInfo, TTI, FoldableInLoop, ----
586 LoopNestMode) && 0
587 canSinkOrHoistInst(I, AA, DT, CurLoop, MSSAU, true, Flags, ORE)) { 0
588 if (sink(I, LI, DT, CurLoop, SafetyInfo, MSSAU, ORE)) { 0
589 if (!FoldableInLoop) { 0
590 ++II; 0
591 salvageDebugInfo(I); 0
592 eraseInstruction(I, *SafetyInfo, MSSAU); 0
593 } ----
594 Changed = true; 0
595 } ----
596 } ----
597 } ----
598 } ----
599 if (VerifyMemorySSA) 0
600 MSSAU.getMemorySSA()->verifyMemorySSA(); 0
601 return Changed; 0
602 } 0
603 ----
604 bool llvm::sinkRegionForLoopNest(DomTreeNode *N, AAResults *AA, LoopInfo *LI, 0
605 DominatorTree *DT, TargetLibraryInfo *TLI, ----
606 TargetTransformInfo *TTI, Loop *CurLoop, ----
607 MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU, ----
608 ICFLoopSafetyInfo *SafetyInfo, ----
609 SinkAndHoistLICMFlags &Flags, ----
610 OptimizationRemarkEmitter *ORE) { ----
611 ----
612 bool Changed = false; 0
613 SmallPriorityWorklist Worklist; 0
614 Worklist.insert(CurLoop); 0
615 appendLoopsToWorklist(*CurLoop, Worklist); 0
616 while (!Worklist.empty()) { 0
617 Loop *L = Worklist.pop_back_val(); 0
618 Changed |= sinkRegion(DT->getNode(L->getHeader()), AA, LI, DT, TLI, TTI, L, 0
619 MSSAU, SafetyInfo, Flags, ORE, CurLoop); ----
620 } ----
621 return Changed; 0
622 } 0
623 ----
624 namespace { ----
625 // This is a helper class for hoistRegion to make it able to hoist control flow ----
626 // in order to be able to hoist phis. The way this works is that we initially ----
627 // start hoisting to the loop preheader, and when we see a loop invariant branch ----
628 // we make note of this. When we then come to hoist an instruction that's ----
629 // conditional on such a branch we duplicate the branch and the relevant control ----
630 // flow, then hoist the instruction into the block corresponding to its original ----
631 // block in the duplicated control flow. ----
632 class ControlFlowHoister { ----
633 private: ----
634 // Information about the loop we are hoisting from ----
635 LoopInfo *LI; ----
636 DominatorTree *DT; ----
637 Loop *CurLoop; ----
638 MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU; ----
639 ----
640 // A map of blocks in the loop to the block their instructions will be hoisted ----
641 // to. ----
642 DenseMap HoistDestinationMap; ----
643 ----
644 // The branches that we can hoist, mapped to the block that marks a ----
645 // convergence point of their control flow. ----
646 DenseMap HoistableBranches; ----
647 ----
648 public: ----
649 ControlFlowHoister(LoopInfo *LI, DominatorTree *DT, Loop *CurLoop, 0
650 MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU) ----
651 : LI(LI), DT(DT), CurLoop(CurLoop), MSSAU(MSSAU) {} 0
652 ----
653 void registerPossiblyHoistableBranch(BranchInst *BI) { 0
654 // We can only hoist conditional branches with loop invariant operands. ----
655 if (!ControlFlowHoisting || !BI->isConditional() || 0
656 !CurLoop->hasLoopInvariantOperands(BI)) 0
657 return; 0
658 ----
659 // The branch destinations need to be in the loop, and we don't gain ----
660 // anything by duplicating conditional branches with duplicate successors, ----
661 // as it's essentially the same as an unconditional branch. ----
662 BasicBlock *TrueDest = BI->getSuccessor(0); 0
663 BasicBlock *FalseDest = BI->getSuccessor(1); 0
664 if (!CurLoop->contains(TrueDest) || !CurLoop->contains(FalseDest) || 0
665 TrueDest == FalseDest) ----
666 return; 0
667 ----
668 // We can hoist BI if one branch destination is the successor of the other, ----
669 // or both have common successor which we check by seeing if the ----
670 // intersection of their successors is non-empty. ----
671 // TODO: This could be expanded to allowing branches where both ends ----
672 // eventually converge to a single block. ----
673 SmallPtrSet TrueDestSucc, FalseDestSucc; 0
674 TrueDestSucc.insert(succ_begin(TrueDest), succ_end(TrueDest)); 0
675 FalseDestSucc.insert(succ_begin(FalseDest), succ_end(FalseDest)); 0
676 BasicBlock *CommonSucc = nullptr; 0
677 if (TrueDestSucc.count(FalseDest)) { 0
678 CommonSucc = FalseDest; 0
679 } else if (FalseDestSucc.count(TrueDest)) { 0
680 CommonSucc = TrueDest; 0
681 } else { ----
682 set_intersect(TrueDestSucc, FalseDestSucc); 0
683 // If there's one common successor use that. ----
684 if (TrueDestSucc.size() == 1) 0
685 CommonSucc = *TrueDestSucc.begin(); 0
686 // If there's more than one pick whichever appears first in the block list ----
687 // (we can't use the value returned by TrueDestSucc.begin() as it's ----
688 // unpredicatable which element gets returned). ----
689 else if (!TrueDestSucc.empty()) { 0
690 Function *F = TrueDest->getParent(); 0
691 auto IsSucc = [&](BasicBlock &BB) { return TrueDestSucc.count(&BB); }; 0
692 auto It = llvm::find_if(*F, IsSucc); 0
693 assert(It != F->end() && "Could not find successor in function"); 0
694 CommonSucc = &*It; 0
695 } ----
696 } ----
697 // The common successor has to be dominated by the branch, as otherwise ----
698 // there will be some other path to the successor that will not be ----
699 // controlled by this branch so any phi we hoist would be controlled by the ----
700 // wrong condition. This also takes care of avoiding hoisting of loop back ----
701 // edges. ----
702 // TODO: In some cases this could be relaxed if the successor is dominated ----
703 // by another block that's been hoisted and we can guarantee that the ----
704 // control flow has been replicated exactly. ----
705 if (CommonSucc && DT->dominates(BI, CommonSucc)) 0
706 HoistableBranches[BI] = CommonSucc; 0
707 } 0
708 ----
709 bool canHoistPHI(PHINode *PN) { 0
710 // The phi must have loop invariant operands. ----
711 if (!ControlFlowHoisting || !CurLoop->hasLoopInvariantOperands(PN)) 0
712 return false; 0
713 // We can hoist phis if the block they are in is the target of hoistable ----
714 // branches which cover all of the predecessors of the block. ----
715 SmallPtrSet PredecessorBlocks; 0
716 BasicBlock *BB = PN->getParent(); 0
717 for (BasicBlock *PredBB : predecessors(BB)) 0
718 PredecessorBlocks.insert(PredBB); 0
719 // If we have less predecessor blocks than predecessors then the phi will ----
720 // have more than one incoming value for the same block which we can't ----
721 // handle. ----
722 // TODO: This could be handled be erasing some of the duplicate incoming ----
723 // values. ----
724 if (PredecessorBlocks.size() != pred_size(BB)) 0
725 return false; 0
726 for (auto &Pair : HoistableBranches) { 0
727 if (Pair.second == BB) { 0
728 // Which blocks are predecessors via this branch depends on if the ----
729 // branch is triangle-like or diamond-like. ----
730 if (Pair.first->getSuccessor(0) == BB) { 0
731 PredecessorBlocks.erase(Pair.first->getParent()); 0
732 PredecessorBlocks.erase(Pair.first->getSuccessor(1)); 0
733 } else if (Pair.first->getSuccessor(1) == BB) { 0
734 PredecessorBlocks.erase(Pair.first->getParent()); 0
735 PredecessorBlocks.erase(Pair.first->getSuccessor(0)); 0
736 } else { ----
737 PredecessorBlocks.erase(Pair.first->getSuccessor(0)); 0
738 PredecessorBlocks.erase(Pair.first->getSuccessor(1)); 0
739 } ----
740 } ----
741 } ----
742 // PredecessorBlocks will now be empty if for every predecessor of BB we ----
743 // found a hoistable branch source. ----
744 return PredecessorBlocks.empty(); 0
745 } 0
746 ----
747 BasicBlock *getOrCreateHoistedBlock(BasicBlock *BB) { 0
748 if (!ControlFlowHoisting) 0
749 return CurLoop->getLoopPreheader(); 0
750 // If BB has already been hoisted, return that ----
751 if (HoistDestinationMap.count(BB)) 0
752 return HoistDestinationMap[BB]; 0
753 ----
754 // Check if this block is conditional based on a pending branch ----
755 auto HasBBAsSuccessor = ----
756 [&](DenseMap::value_type &Pair) { 0
757 return BB != Pair.second && (Pair.first->getSuccessor(0) == BB || 0
758 Pair.first->getSuccessor(1) == BB); 0
759 }; 0
760 auto It = llvm::find_if(HoistableBranches, HasBBAsSuccessor); 0
761 ----
762 // If not involved in a pending branch, hoist to preheader ----
763 BasicBlock *InitialPreheader = CurLoop->getLoopPreheader(); 0
764 if (It == HoistableBranches.end()) { 0
765 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "LICM using " 0
766 << InitialPreheader->getNameOrAsOperand() ----
767 << " as hoist destination for " ----
768 << BB->getNameOrAsOperand() << "\n"); ----
769 HoistDestinationMap[BB] = InitialPreheader; 0
770 return InitialPreheader; 0
771 } ----
772 BranchInst *BI = It->first; 0
773 assert(std::find_if(++It, HoistableBranches.end(), HasBBAsSuccessor) == 0
774 HoistableBranches.end() && ----
775 "BB is expected to be the target of at most one branch"); ----
776 ----
777 LLVMContext &C = BB->getContext(); 0
778 BasicBlock *TrueDest = BI->getSuccessor(0); 0
779 BasicBlock *FalseDest = BI->getSuccessor(1); 0
780 BasicBlock *CommonSucc = HoistableBranches[BI]; 0
781 BasicBlock *HoistTarget = getOrCreateHoistedBlock(BI->getParent()); 0
782 ----
783 // Create hoisted versions of blocks that currently don't have them ----
784 auto CreateHoistedBlock = [&](BasicBlock *Orig) { 0
785 if (HoistDestinationMap.count(Orig)) 0
786 return HoistDestinationMap[Orig]; 0
787 BasicBlock *New = ----
788 BasicBlock::Create(C, Orig->getName() + ".licm", Orig->getParent()); 0
789 HoistDestinationMap[Orig] = New; 0
790 DT->addNewBlock(New, HoistTarget); 0
791 if (CurLoop->getParentLoop()) 0
792 CurLoop->getParentLoop()->addBasicBlockToLoop(New, *LI); 0
793 ++NumCreatedBlocks; 0
794 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "LICM created " << New->getName() 0
795 << " as hoist destination for " << Orig->getName() ----
796 << "\n"); ----
797 return New; 0
798 }; 0
799 BasicBlock *HoistTrueDest = CreateHoistedBlock(TrueDest); 0
800 BasicBlock *HoistFalseDest = CreateHoistedBlock(FalseDest); 0
801 BasicBlock *HoistCommonSucc = CreateHoistedBlock(CommonSucc); 0
802 ----
803 // Link up these blocks with branches. ----
804 if (!HoistCommonSucc->getTerminator()) { 0
805 // The new common successor we've generated will branch to whatever that ----
806 // hoist target branched to. ----
807 BasicBlock *TargetSucc = HoistTarget->getSingleSuccessor(); 0
808 assert(TargetSucc && "Expected hoist target to have a single successor"); 0
809 HoistCommonSucc->moveBefore(TargetSucc); 0
810 BranchInst::Create(TargetSucc, HoistCommonSucc); 0
811 } ----
812 if (!HoistTrueDest->getTerminator()) { 0
813 HoistTrueDest->moveBefore(HoistCommonSucc); 0
814 BranchInst::Create(HoistCommonSucc, HoistTrueDest); 0
815 } ----
816 if (!HoistFalseDest->getTerminator()) { 0
817 HoistFalseDest->moveBefore(HoistCommonSucc); 0
818 BranchInst::Create(HoistCommonSucc, HoistFalseDest); 0
819 } ----
820 ----
821 // If BI is being cloned to what was originally the preheader then ----
822 // HoistCommonSucc will now be the new preheader. ----
823 if (HoistTarget == InitialPreheader) { 0
824 // Phis in the loop header now need to use the new preheader. ----
825 InitialPreheader->replaceSuccessorsPhiUsesWith(HoistCommonSucc); 0
826 MSSAU.wireOldPredecessorsToNewImmediatePredecessor( 0
827 HoistTarget->getSingleSuccessor(), HoistCommonSucc, {HoistTarget}); ----
828 // The new preheader dominates the loop header. ----
829 DomTreeNode *PreheaderNode = DT->getNode(HoistCommonSucc); 0
830 DomTreeNode *HeaderNode = DT->getNode(CurLoop->getHeader()); 0
831 DT->changeImmediateDominator(HeaderNode, PreheaderNode); 0
832 // The preheader hoist destination is now the new preheader, with the ----
833 // exception of the hoist destination of this branch. ----
834 for (auto &Pair : HoistDestinationMap) 0
835 if (Pair.second == InitialPreheader && Pair.first != BI->getParent()) 0
836 Pair.second = HoistCommonSucc; 0
837 } ----
838 ----
839 // Now finally clone BI. ----
840 ReplaceInstWithInst( 0
841 HoistTarget->getTerminator(), ----
842 BranchInst::Create(HoistTrueDest, HoistFalseDest, BI->getCondition())); 0
843 ++NumClonedBranches; 0
844 ----
845 assert(CurLoop->getLoopPreheader() && 0
846 "Hoisting blocks should not have destroyed preheader"); ----
847 return HoistDestinationMap[BB]; 0
848 } ----
849 }; ----
850 } // namespace ----
851 ----
852 /// Walk the specified region of the CFG (defined by all blocks dominated by ----
853 /// the specified block, and that are in the current loop) in depth first ----
854 /// order w.r.t the DominatorTree. This allows us to visit definitions before ----
855 /// uses, allowing us to hoist a loop body in one pass without iteration. ----
856 /// ----
857 bool llvm::hoistRegion(DomTreeNode *N, AAResults *AA, LoopInfo *LI, 0
858 DominatorTree *DT, AssumptionCache *AC, ----
859 TargetLibraryInfo *TLI, Loop *CurLoop, ----
860 MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU, ScalarEvolution *SE, ----
861 ICFLoopSafetyInfo *SafetyInfo, ----
862 SinkAndHoistLICMFlags &Flags, ----
863 OptimizationRemarkEmitter *ORE, bool LoopNestMode, ----
864 bool AllowSpeculation) { ----
865 // Verify inputs. ----
866 assert(N != nullptr && AA != nullptr && LI != nullptr && DT != nullptr && 0
867 CurLoop != nullptr && SafetyInfo != nullptr && ----
868 "Unexpected input to hoistRegion."); ----
869 ----
870 ControlFlowHoister CFH(LI, DT, CurLoop, MSSAU); 0
871 ----
872 // Keep track of instructions that have been hoisted, as they may need to be ----
873 // re-hoisted if they end up not dominating all of their uses. ----
874 SmallVector HoistedInstructions; 0
875 ----
876 // For PHI hoisting to work we need to hoist blocks before their successors. ----
877 // We can do this by iterating through the blocks in the loop in reverse ----
878 // post-order. ----
879 LoopBlocksRPO Worklist(CurLoop); 0
880 Worklist.perform(LI); 0
881 bool Changed = false; 0
882 BasicBlock *Preheader = CurLoop->getLoopPreheader(); 0
883 for (BasicBlock *BB : Worklist) { 0
884 // Only need to process the contents of this block if it is not part of a ----
885 // subloop (which would already have been processed). ----
886 if (!LoopNestMode && inSubLoop(BB, CurLoop, LI)) 0
887 continue; 0
888 ----
889 for (Instruction &I : llvm::make_early_inc_range(*BB)) { 0
890 // Try hoisting the instruction out to the preheader. We can only do ----
891 // this if all of the operands of the instruction are loop invariant and ----
892 // if it is safe to hoist the instruction. We also check block frequency ----
893 // to make sure instruction only gets hoisted into colder blocks. ----
894 // TODO: It may be safe to hoist if we are hoisting to a conditional block ----
895 // and we have accurately duplicated the control flow from the loop header ----
896 // to that block. ----
897 if (CurLoop->hasLoopInvariantOperands(&I) && 0
898 canSinkOrHoistInst(I, AA, DT, CurLoop, MSSAU, true, Flags, ORE) && 0
899 isSafeToExecuteUnconditionally( 0
900 I, DT, TLI, CurLoop, SafetyInfo, ORE, ----
901 Preheader->getTerminator(), AC, AllowSpeculation)) { 0
902 hoist(I, DT, CurLoop, CFH.getOrCreateHoistedBlock(BB), SafetyInfo, 0
903 MSSAU, SE, ORE); ----
904 HoistedInstructions.push_back(&I); 0
905 Changed = true; 0
906 continue; 0
907 } ----
908 ----
909 // Attempt to remove floating point division out of the loop by ----
910 // converting it to a reciprocal multiplication. ----
911 if (I.getOpcode() == Instruction::FDiv && I.hasAllowReciprocal() && 0
912 CurLoop->isLoopInvariant(I.getOperand(1))) { 0
913 auto Divisor = I.getOperand(1); 0
914 auto One = llvm::ConstantFP::get(Divisor->getType(), 1.0); 0
915 auto ReciprocalDivisor = BinaryOperator::CreateFDiv(One, Divisor); 0
916 ReciprocalDivisor->setFastMathFlags(I.getFastMathFlags()); 0
917 SafetyInfo->insertInstructionTo(ReciprocalDivisor, I.getParent()); 0
918 ReciprocalDivisor->insertBefore(&I); 0
919 ----
920 auto Product = ----
921 BinaryOperator::CreateFMul(I.getOperand(0), ReciprocalDivisor); 0
922 Product->setFastMathFlags(I.getFastMathFlags()); 0
923 SafetyInfo->insertInstructionTo(Product, I.getParent()); 0
924 Product->insertAfter(&I); 0
925 I.replaceAllUsesWith(Product); 0
926 eraseInstruction(I, *SafetyInfo, MSSAU); 0
927 ----
928 hoist(*ReciprocalDivisor, DT, CurLoop, CFH.getOrCreateHoistedBlock(BB), 0
929 SafetyInfo, MSSAU, SE, ORE); ----
930 HoistedInstructions.push_back(ReciprocalDivisor); 0
931 Changed = true; 0
932 continue; 0
933 } 0
934 ----
935 auto IsInvariantStart = [&](Instruction &I) { 0
936 using namespace PatternMatch; ----
937 return I.use_empty() && 0
938 match(&I, m_Intrinsic()); 0
939 }; ----
940 auto MustExecuteWithoutWritesBefore = [&](Instruction &I) { 0
941 return SafetyInfo->isGuaranteedToExecute(I, DT, CurLoop) && 0
942 SafetyInfo->doesNotWriteMemoryBefore(I, CurLoop); 0
943 }; 0
944 if ((IsInvariantStart(I) || isGuard(&I)) && 0
945 CurLoop->hasLoopInvariantOperands(&I) && 0
946 MustExecuteWithoutWritesBefore(I)) { 0
947 hoist(I, DT, CurLoop, CFH.getOrCreateHoistedBlock(BB), SafetyInfo, 0
948 MSSAU, SE, ORE); ----
949 HoistedInstructions.push_back(&I); 0
950 Changed = true; 0
951 continue; 0
952 } ----
953 ----
954 if (PHINode *PN = dyn_cast(&I)) { 0
955 if (CFH.canHoistPHI(PN)) { 0
956 // Redirect incoming blocks first to ensure that we create hoisted ----
957 // versions of those blocks before we hoist the phi. ----
958 for (unsigned int i = 0; i < PN->getNumIncomingValues(); ++i) 0
959 PN->setIncomingBlock( 0
960 i, CFH.getOrCreateHoistedBlock(PN->getIncomingBlock(i))); ----
961 hoist(*PN, DT, CurLoop, CFH.getOrCreateHoistedBlock(BB), SafetyInfo, 0
962 MSSAU, SE, ORE); ----
963 assert(DT->dominates(PN, BB) && "Conditional PHIs not expected"); 0
964 Changed = true; 0
965 continue; 0
966 } 0
967 } ----
968 ----
969 // Try to reassociate instructions so that part of computations can be ----
970 // done out of loop. ----
971 if (hoistArithmetics(I, *CurLoop, *SafetyInfo, MSSAU, AC, DT)) { 0
972 Changed = true; 0
973 continue; 0
974 } ----
975 ----
976 // Remember possibly hoistable branches so we can actually hoist them ----
977 // later if needed. ----
978 if (BranchInst *BI = dyn_cast(&I)) 0
979 CFH.registerPossiblyHoistableBranch(BI); 0
980 } ----
981 } ----
982 ----
983 // If we hoisted instructions to a conditional block they may not dominate ----
984 // their uses that weren't hoisted (such as phis where some operands are not ----
985 // loop invariant). If so make them unconditional by moving them to their ----
986 // immediate dominator. We iterate through the instructions in reverse order ----
987 // which ensures that when we rehoist an instruction we rehoist its operands, ----
988 // and also keep track of where in the block we are rehoisting to to make sure ----
989 // that we rehoist instructions before the instructions that use them. ----
990 Instruction *HoistPoint = nullptr; 0
991 if (ControlFlowHoisting) { 0
992 for (Instruction *I : reverse(HoistedInstructions)) { 0
993 if (!llvm::all_of(I->uses(), 0
994 [&](Use &U) { return DT->dominates(I, U); })) { 0
995 BasicBlock *Dominator = ----
996 DT->getNode(I->getParent())->getIDom()->getBlock(); 0
997 if (!HoistPoint || !DT->dominates(HoistPoint->getParent(), Dominator)) { 0
998 if (HoistPoint) 0
999 assert(DT->dominates(Dominator, HoistPoint->getParent()) && 0
1000 "New hoist point expected to dominate old hoist point"); ----
1001 HoistPoint = Dominator->getTerminator(); 0
1002 } ----
1003 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "LICM rehoisting to " 0
1004 << HoistPoint->getParent()->getNameOrAsOperand() ----
1005 << ": " << *I << "\n"); ----
1006 moveInstructionBefore(*I, *HoistPoint, *SafetyInfo, MSSAU, SE); 0
1007 HoistPoint = I; 0
1008 Changed = true; 0
1009 } ----
1010 } ----
1011 } ----
1012 if (VerifyMemorySSA) 0
1013 MSSAU.getMemorySSA()->verifyMemorySSA(); 0
1014 ----
1015 // Now that we've finished hoisting make sure that LI and DT are still ----
1016 // valid. ----
1017 #ifdef EXPENSIVE_CHECKS ----
1018 if (Changed) { ----
1019 assert(DT->verify(DominatorTree::VerificationLevel::Fast) && ----
1020 "Dominator tree verification failed"); ----
1021 LI->verify(*DT); ----
1022 } ----
1023 #endif ----
1024 ----
1025 return Changed; 0
1026 } 0
1027 ----
1028 // Return true if LI is invariant within scope of the loop. LI is invariant if ----
1029 // CurLoop is dominated by an invariant.start representing the same memory ----
1030 // location and size as the memory location LI loads from, and also the ----
1031 // invariant.start has no uses. ----
1032 static bool isLoadInvariantInLoop(LoadInst *LI, DominatorTree *DT, 0
1033 Loop *CurLoop) { ----
1034 Value *Addr = LI->getOperand(0); 0
1035 const DataLayout &DL = LI->getModule()->getDataLayout(); 0
1036 const TypeSize LocSizeInBits = DL.getTypeSizeInBits(LI->getType()); 0
1037 ----
1038 // It is not currently possible for clang to generate an invariant.start ----
1039 // intrinsic with scalable vector types because we don't support thread local ----
1040 // sizeless types and we don't permit sizeless types in structs or classes. ----
1041 // Furthermore, even if support is added for this in future the intrinsic ----
1042 // itself is defined to have a size of -1 for variable sized objects. This ----
1043 // makes it impossible to verify if the intrinsic envelops our region of ----
1044 // interest. For example, both and ----
1045 // types would have a -1 parameter, but the former is clearly double the size ----
1046 // of the latter. ----
1047 if (LocSizeInBits.isScalable()) 0
1048 return false; 0
1049 ----
1050 // if the type is i8 addrspace(x)*, we know this is the type of ----
1051 // llvm.invariant.start operand ----
1052 auto *PtrInt8Ty = PointerType::get(Type::getInt8Ty(LI->getContext()), 0
1053 LI->getPointerAddressSpace()); ----
1054 unsigned BitcastsVisited = 0; 0
1055 // Look through bitcasts until we reach the i8* type (this is invariant.start ----
1056 // operand type). ----
1057 while (Addr->getType() != PtrInt8Ty) { 0
1058 auto *BC = dyn_cast(Addr); 0
1059 // Avoid traversing high number of bitcast uses. ----
1060 if (++BitcastsVisited > MaxNumUsesTraversed || !BC) 0
1061 return false; 0
1062 Addr = BC->getOperand(0); 0
1063 } ----
1064 // If we've ended up at a global/constant, bail. We shouldn't be looking at ----
1065 // uselists for non-local Values in a loop pass. ----
1066 if (isa(Addr)) 0
1067 return false; 0
1068 ----
1069 unsigned UsesVisited = 0; 0
1070 // Traverse all uses of the load operand value, to see if invariant.start is ----
1071 // one of the uses, and whether it dominates the load instruction. ----
1072 for (auto *U : Addr->users()) { 0
1073 // Avoid traversing for Load operand with high number of users. ----
1074 if (++UsesVisited > MaxNumUsesTraversed) 0
1075 return false; 0
1076 IntrinsicInst *II = dyn_cast(U); 0
1077 // If there are escaping uses of invariant.start instruction, the load maybe ----
1078 // non-invariant. ----
1079 if (!II || II->getIntrinsicID() != Intrinsic::invariant_start || 0
1080 !II->use_empty()) 0
1081 continue; 0
1082 ConstantInt *InvariantSize = cast(II->getArgOperand(0)); 0
1083 // The intrinsic supports having a -1 argument for variable sized objects ----
1084 // so we should check for that here. ----
1085 if (InvariantSize->isNegative()) 0
1086 continue; 0
1087 uint64_t InvariantSizeInBits = InvariantSize->getSExtValue() * 8; 0
1088 // Confirm the invariant.start location size contains the load operand size ----
1089 // in bits. Also, the invariant.start should dominate the load, and we ----
1090 // should not hoist the load out of a loop that contains this dominating ----
1091 // invariant.start. ----
1092 if (LocSizeInBits.getFixedValue() <= InvariantSizeInBits && 0
1093 DT->properlyDominates(II->getParent(), CurLoop->getHeader())) 0
1094 return true; 0
1095 } ----
1096 ----
1097 return false; 0
1098 } ----
1099 ----
1100 namespace { ----
1101 /// Return true if-and-only-if we know how to (mechanically) both hoist and ----
1102 /// sink a given instruction out of a loop. Does not address legality ----
1103 /// concerns such as aliasing or speculation safety. ----
1104 bool isHoistableAndSinkableInst(Instruction &I) { 0
1105 // Only these instructions are hoistable/sinkable. ----
1106 return (isa(I) || isa(I) || isa(I) || 0
1107 isa(I) || isa(I) || isa(I) || 0
1108 isa(I) || isa(I) || 0
1109 isa(I) || isa(I) || 0
1110 isa(I) || isa(I) || 0
1111 isa(I) || isa(I) || 0
1112 isa(I) || isa(I)); 0
1113 } ----
1114 /// Return true if MSSA knows there are no MemoryDefs in the loop. ----
1115 bool isReadOnly(const MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU, const Loop *L) { 0
1116 for (auto *BB : L->getBlocks()) 0
1117 if (MSSAU.getMemorySSA()->getBlockDefs(BB)) 0
1118 return false; 0
1119 return true; 0
1120 } ----
1121 ----
1122 /// Return true if I is the only Instruction with a MemoryAccess in L. ----
1123 bool isOnlyMemoryAccess(const Instruction *I, const Loop *L, 0
1124 const MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU) { ----
1125 for (auto *BB : L->getBlocks()) 0
1126 if (auto *Accs = MSSAU.getMemorySSA()->getBlockAccesses(BB)) { 0
1127 int NotAPhi = 0; 0
1128 for (const auto &Acc : *Accs) { 0
1129 if (isa(&Acc)) 0
1130 continue; 0
1131 const auto *MUD = cast(&Acc); 0
1132 if (MUD->getMemoryInst() != I || NotAPhi++ == 1) 0
1133 return false; 0
1134 } ----
1135 } ----
1136 return true; 0
1137 } ----
1138 } ----
1139 ----
1140 static MemoryAccess *getClobberingMemoryAccess(MemorySSA &MSSA, 0
1141 BatchAAResults &BAA, ----
1142 SinkAndHoistLICMFlags &Flags, ----
1143 MemoryUseOrDef *MA) { ----
1144 // See declaration of SetLicmMssaOptCap for usage details. ----
1145 if (Flags.tooManyClobberingCalls()) 0
1146 return MA->getDefiningAccess(); 0
1147 ----
1148 MemoryAccess *Source = ----
1149 MSSA.getSkipSelfWalker()->getClobberingMemoryAccess(MA, BAA); 0
1150 Flags.incrementClobberingCalls(); 0
1151 return Source; 0
1152 } ----
1153 ----
1154 bool llvm::canSinkOrHoistInst(Instruction &I, AAResults *AA, DominatorTree *DT, 0
1155 Loop *CurLoop, MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU, ----
1156 bool TargetExecutesOncePerLoop, ----
1157 SinkAndHoistLICMFlags &Flags, ----
1158 OptimizationRemarkEmitter *ORE) { ----
1159 // If we don't understand the instruction, bail early. ----
1160 if (!isHoistableAndSinkableInst(I)) 0
1161 return false; 0
1162 ----
1163 MemorySSA *MSSA = MSSAU.getMemorySSA(); 0
1164 // Loads have extra constraints we have to verify before we can hoist them. ----
1165 if (LoadInst *LI = dyn_cast(&I)) { 0
1166 if (!LI->isUnordered()) 0
1167 return false; // Don't sink/hoist volatile or ordered atomic loads! 0
1168 ----
1169 // Loads from constant memory are always safe to move, even if they end up ----
1170 // in the same alias set as something that ends up being modified. ----
1171 if (!isModSet(AA->getModRefInfoMask(LI->getOperand(0)))) 0
1172 return true; 0
1173 if (LI->hasMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_invariant_load)) 0
1174 return true; 0
1175 ----
1176 if (LI->isAtomic() && !TargetExecutesOncePerLoop) 0
1177 return false; // Don't risk duplicating unordered loads 0
1178 ----
1179 // This checks for an invariant.start dominating the load. ----
1180 if (isLoadInvariantInLoop(LI, DT, CurLoop)) 0
1181 return true; 0
1182 ----
1183 auto MU = cast(MSSA->getMemoryAccess(LI)); 0
1184 ----
1185 bool InvariantGroup = LI->hasMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_invariant_group); 0
1186 ----
1187 bool Invalidated = pointerInvalidatedByLoop( 0
1188 MSSA, MU, CurLoop, I, Flags, InvariantGroup); ----
1189 // Check loop-invariant address because this may also be a sinkable load ----
1190 // whose address is not necessarily loop-invariant. ----
1191 if (ORE && Invalidated && CurLoop->isLoopInvariant(LI->getPointerOperand())) 0
1192 ORE->emit([&]() { 0
1193 return OptimizationRemarkMissed( 0
1194 DEBUG_TYPE, "LoadWithLoopInvariantAddressInvalidated", LI) 0
1195 << "failed to move load with loop-invariant address " ----
1196 "because the loop may invalidate its value"; 0
1197 }); ----
1198 ----
1199 return !Invalidated; 0
1200 } else if (CallInst *CI = dyn_cast(&I)) { 0
1201 // Don't sink or hoist dbg info; it's legal, but not useful. ----
1202 if (isa(I)) 0
1203 return false; 0
1204 ----
1205 // Don't sink calls which can throw. ----
1206 if (CI->mayThrow()) 0
1207 return false; 0
1208 ----
1209 // Convergent attribute has been used on operations that involve ----
1210 // inter-thread communication which results are implicitly affected by the ----
1211 // enclosing control flows. It is not safe to hoist or sink such operations ----
1212 // across control flow. ----
1213 if (CI->isConvergent()) 0
1214 return false; 0
1215 ----
1216 using namespace PatternMatch; ----
1217 if (match(CI, m_Intrinsic())) 0
1218 // Assumes don't actually alias anything or throw ----
1219 return true; 0
1220 ----
1221 // Handle simple cases by querying alias analysis. ----
1222 MemoryEffects Behavior = AA->getMemoryEffects(CI); 0
1223 ----
1224 // FIXME: we don't handle the semantics of thread local well. So that the ----
1225 // address of thread locals are fake constants in coroutines. So We forbid ----
1226 // to treat onlyReadsMemory call in coroutines as constants now. Note that ----
1227 // it is possible to hide a thread local access in a onlyReadsMemory call. ----
1228 // Remove this check after we handle the semantics of thread locals well. ----
1229 if (Behavior.onlyReadsMemory() && CI->getFunction()->isPresplitCoroutine()) 0
1230 return false; 0
1231 ----
1232 if (Behavior.doesNotAccessMemory()) 0
1233 return true; 0
1234 if (Behavior.onlyReadsMemory()) { 0
1235 // A readonly argmemonly function only reads from memory pointed to by ----
1236 // it's arguments with arbitrary offsets. If we can prove there are no ----
1237 // writes to this memory in the loop, we can hoist or sink. ----
1238 if (Behavior.onlyAccessesArgPointees()) { 0
1239 // TODO: expand to writeable arguments ----
1240 for (Value *Op : CI->args()) 0
1241 if (Op->getType()->isPointerTy() && 0
1242 pointerInvalidatedByLoop( 0
1243 MSSA, cast(MSSA->getMemoryAccess(CI)), CurLoop, I, ----
1244 Flags, /*InvariantGroup=*/false)) ----
1245 return false; 0
1246 return true; 0
1247 } ----
1248 ----
1249 // If this call only reads from memory and there are no writes to memory ----
1250 // in the loop, we can hoist or sink the call as appropriate. ----
1251 if (isReadOnly(MSSAU, CurLoop)) 0
1252 return true; 0
1253 } ----
1254 ----
1255 // FIXME: This should use mod/ref information to see if we can hoist or ----
1256 // sink the call. ----
1257 ----
1258 return false; 0
1259 } else if (auto *FI = dyn_cast(&I)) { 0
1260 // Fences alias (most) everything to provide ordering. For the moment, ----
1261 // just give up if there are any other memory operations in the loop. ----
1262 return isOnlyMemoryAccess(FI, CurLoop, MSSAU); 0
1263 } else if (auto *SI = dyn_cast(&I)) { 0
1264 if (!SI->isUnordered()) 0
1265 return false; // Don't sink/hoist volatile or ordered atomic store! 0
1266 ----
1267 // We can only hoist a store that we can prove writes a value which is not ----
1268 // read or overwritten within the loop. For those cases, we fallback to ----
1269 // load store promotion instead. TODO: We can extend this to cases where ----
1270 // there is exactly one write to the location and that write dominates an ----
1271 // arbitrary number of reads in the loop. ----
1272 if (isOnlyMemoryAccess(SI, CurLoop, MSSAU)) 0
1273 return true; 0
1274 // If there are more accesses than the Promotion cap, then give up as we're ----
1275 // not walking a list that long. ----
1276 if (Flags.tooManyMemoryAccesses()) 0
1277 return false; 0
1278 ----
1279 auto *SIMD = MSSA->getMemoryAccess(SI); 0
1280 BatchAAResults BAA(*AA); 0
1281 auto *Source = getClobberingMemoryAccess(*MSSA, BAA, Flags, SIMD); 0
1282 // Make sure there are no clobbers inside the loop. ----
1283 if (!MSSA->isLiveOnEntryDef(Source) && 0
1284 CurLoop->contains(Source->getBlock())) 0
1285 return false; 0
1286 ----
1287 // If there are interfering Uses (i.e. their defining access is in the ----
1288 // loop), or ordered loads (stored as Defs!), don't move this store. ----
1289 // Could do better here, but this is conservatively correct. ----
1290 // TODO: Cache set of Uses on the first walk in runOnLoop, update when ----
1291 // moving accesses. Can also extend to dominating uses. ----
1292 for (auto *BB : CurLoop->getBlocks()) 0
1293 if (auto *Accesses = MSSA->getBlockAccesses(BB)) { 0
1294 for (const auto &MA : *Accesses) 0
1295 if (const auto *MU = dyn_cast(&MA)) { 0
1296 auto *MD = getClobberingMemoryAccess(*MSSA, BAA, Flags, 0
1297 const_cast(MU)); ----
1298 if (!MSSA->isLiveOnEntryDef(MD) && 0
1299 CurLoop->contains(MD->getBlock())) 0
1300 return false; 0
1301 // Disable hoisting past potentially interfering loads. Optimized ----
1302 // Uses may point to an access outside the loop, as getClobbering ----
1303 // checks the previous iteration when walking the backedge. ----
1304 // FIXME: More precise: no Uses that alias SI. ----
1305 if (!Flags.getIsSink() && !MSSA->dominates(SIMD, MU)) 0
1306 return false; 0
1307 } else if (const auto *MD = dyn_cast(&MA)) { 0
1308 if (auto *LI = dyn_cast(MD->getMemoryInst())) { 0
1309 (void)LI; // Silence warning. ----
1310 assert(!LI->isUnordered() && "Expected unordered load"); 0
1311 return false; 0
1312 } ----
1313 // Any call, while it may not be clobbering SI, it may be a use. ----
1314 if (auto *CI = dyn_cast(MD->getMemoryInst())) { 0
1315 // Check if the call may read from the memory location written ----
1316 // to by SI. Check CI's attributes and arguments; the number of ----
1317 // such checks performed is limited above by NoOfMemAccTooLarge. ----
1318 ModRefInfo MRI = BAA.getModRefInfo(CI, MemoryLocation::get(SI)); 0
1319 if (isModOrRefSet(MRI)) 0
1320 return false; 0
1321 } ----
1322 } ----
1323 } ----
1324 return true; 0
1325 } 0
1326 ----
1327 assert(!I.mayReadOrWriteMemory() && "unhandled aliasing"); 0
1328 ----
1329 // We've established mechanical ability and aliasing, it's up to the caller ----
1330 // to check fault safety ----
1331 return true; 0
1332 } ----
1333 ----
1334 /// Returns true if a PHINode is a trivially replaceable with an ----
1335 /// Instruction. ----
1336 /// This is true when all incoming values are that instruction. ----
1337 /// This pattern occurs most often with LCSSA PHI nodes. ----
1338 /// ----
1339 static bool isTriviallyReplaceablePHI(const PHINode &PN, const Instruction &I) { 0
1340 for (const Value *IncValue : PN.incoming_values()) 0
1341 if (IncValue != &I) 0
1342 return false; 0
1343 ----
1344 return true; 0
1345 } ----
1346 ----
1347 /// Return true if the instruction is foldable in the loop. ----
1348 static bool isFoldableInLoop(const Instruction &I, const Loop *CurLoop, 0
1349 const TargetTransformInfo *TTI) { ----
1350 if (auto *GEP = dyn_cast(&I)) { 0
1351 InstructionCost CostI = ----
1352 TTI->getInstructionCost(&I, TargetTransformInfo::TCK_SizeAndLatency); 0
1353 if (CostI != TargetTransformInfo::TCC_Free) 0
1354 return false; 0
1355 // For a GEP, we cannot simply use getInstructionCost because currently ----
1356 // it optimistically assumes that a GEP will fold into addressing mode ----
1357 // regardless of its users. ----
1358 const BasicBlock *BB = GEP->getParent(); 0
1359 for (const User *U : GEP->users()) { 0
1360 const Instruction *UI = cast(U); 0
1361 if (CurLoop->contains(UI) && 0
1362 (BB != UI->getParent() || 0
1363 (!isa(UI) && !isa(UI)))) 0
1364 return false; 0
1365 } ----
1366 return true; 0
1367 } ----
1368 ----
1369 return false; 0
1370 } ----
1371 ----
1372 /// Return true if the only users of this instruction are outside of ----
1373 /// the loop. If this is true, we can sink the instruction to the exit ----
1374 /// blocks of the loop. ----
1375 /// ----
1376 /// We also return true if the instruction could be folded away in lowering. ----
1377 /// (e.g., a GEP can be folded into a load as an addressing mode in the loop). ----
1378 static bool isNotUsedOrFoldableInLoop(const Instruction &I, const Loop *CurLoop, 0
1379 const LoopSafetyInfo *SafetyInfo, ----
1380 TargetTransformInfo *TTI, ----
1381 bool &FoldableInLoop, bool LoopNestMode) { ----
1382 const auto &BlockColors = SafetyInfo->getBlockColors(); 0
1383 bool IsFoldable = isFoldableInLoop(I, CurLoop, TTI); 0
1384 for (const User *U : I.users()) { 0
1385 const Instruction *UI = cast(U); 0
1386 if (const PHINode *PN = dyn_cast(UI)) { 0
1387 const BasicBlock *BB = PN->getParent(); 0
1388 // We cannot sink uses in catchswitches. ----
1389 if (isa(BB->getTerminator())) 0
1390 return false; 0
1391 ----
1392 // We need to sink a callsite to a unique funclet. Avoid sinking if the ----
1393 // phi use is too muddled. ----
1394 if (isa(I)) 0
1395 if (!BlockColors.empty() && 0
1396 BlockColors.find(const_cast(BB))->second.size() != 1) 0
1397 return false; 0
1398 ----
1399 if (LoopNestMode) { 0
1400 while (isa(UI) && UI->hasOneUser() && 0
1401 UI->getNumOperands() == 1) { 0
1402 if (!CurLoop->contains(UI)) 0
1403 break; 0
1404 UI = cast(UI->user_back()); 0
1405 } ----
1406 } ----
1407 } ----
1408 ----
1409 if (CurLoop->contains(UI)) { 0
1410 if (IsFoldable) { 0
1411 FoldableInLoop = true; 0
1412 continue; 0
1413 } ----
1414 return false; 0
1415 } ----
1416 } ----
1417 return true; 0
1418 } ----
1419 ----
1420 static Instruction *cloneInstructionInExitBlock( 0
1421 Instruction &I, BasicBlock &ExitBlock, PHINode &PN, const LoopInfo *LI, ----
1422 const LoopSafetyInfo *SafetyInfo, MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU) { ----
1423 Instruction *New; ----
1424 if (auto *CI = dyn_cast(&I)) { 0
1425 const auto &BlockColors = SafetyInfo->getBlockColors(); 0
1426 ----
1427 // Sinking call-sites need to be handled differently from other ----
1428 // instructions. The cloned call-site needs a funclet bundle operand ----
1429 // appropriate for its location in the CFG. ----
1430 SmallVector OpBundles; 0
1431 for (unsigned BundleIdx = 0, BundleEnd = CI->getNumOperandBundles(); 0
1432 BundleIdx != BundleEnd; ++BundleIdx) { 0
1433 OperandBundleUse Bundle = CI->getOperandBundleAt(BundleIdx); 0
1434 if (Bundle.getTagID() == LLVMContext::OB_funclet) 0
1435 continue; 0
1436 ----
1437 OpBundles.emplace_back(Bundle); 0
1438 } ----
1439 ----
1440 if (!BlockColors.empty()) { 0
1441 const ColorVector &CV = BlockColors.find(&ExitBlock)->second; 0
1442 assert(CV.size() == 1 && "non-unique color for exit block!"); 0
1443 BasicBlock *BBColor = CV.front(); 0
1444 Instruction *EHPad = BBColor->getFirstNonPHI(); 0
1445 if (EHPad->isEHPad()) 0
1446 OpBundles.emplace_back("funclet", EHPad); 0
1447 } ----
1448 ----
1449 New = CallInst::Create(CI, OpBundles); 0
1450 } else { 0
1451 New = I.clone(); 0
1452 } ----
1453 ----
1454 New->insertInto(&ExitBlock, ExitBlock.getFirstInsertionPt()); 0
1455 if (!I.getName().empty()) 0
1456 New->setName(I.getName() + ".le"); 0
1457 ----
1458 if (MSSAU.getMemorySSA()->getMemoryAccess(&I)) { 0
1459 // Create a new MemoryAccess and let MemorySSA set its defining access. ----
1460 MemoryAccess *NewMemAcc = MSSAU.createMemoryAccessInBB( 0
1461 New, nullptr, New->getParent(), MemorySSA::Beginning); 0
1462 if (NewMemAcc) { 0
1463 if (auto *MemDef = dyn_cast(NewMemAcc)) 0
1464 MSSAU.insertDef(MemDef, /*RenameUses=*/true); 0
1465 else { ----
1466 auto *MemUse = cast(NewMemAcc); 0
1467 MSSAU.insertUse(MemUse, /*RenameUses=*/true); 0
1468 } ----
1469 } ----
1470 } ----
1471 ----
1472 // Build LCSSA PHI nodes for any in-loop operands (if legal). Note that ----
1473 // this is particularly cheap because we can rip off the PHI node that we're ----
1474 // replacing for the number and blocks of the predecessors. ----
1475 // OPT: If this shows up in a profile, we can instead finish sinking all ----
1476 // invariant instructions, and then walk their operands to re-establish ----
1477 // LCSSA. That will eliminate creating PHI nodes just to nuke them when ----
1478 // sinking bottom-up. ----
1479 for (Use &Op : New->operands()) 0
1480 if (LI->wouldBeOutOfLoopUseRequiringLCSSA(Op.get(), PN.getParent())) { 0
1481 auto *OInst = cast(Op.get()); 0
1482 PHINode *OpPN = ----
1483 PHINode::Create(OInst->getType(), PN.getNumIncomingValues(), 0
1484 OInst->getName() + ".lcssa", &ExitBlock.front()); 0
1485 for (unsigned i = 0, e = PN.getNumIncomingValues(); i != e; ++i) 0
1486 OpPN->addIncoming(OInst, PN.getIncomingBlock(i)); 0
1487 Op = OpPN; 0
1488 } ----
1489 return New; 0
1490 } ----
1491 ----
1492 static void eraseInstruction(Instruction &I, ICFLoopSafetyInfo &SafetyInfo, 0
1493 MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU) { ----
1494 MSSAU.removeMemoryAccess(&I); 0
1495 SafetyInfo.removeInstruction(&I); 0
1496 I.eraseFromParent(); 0
1497 } 0
1498 ----
1499 static void moveInstructionBefore(Instruction &I, Instruction &Dest, 0
1500 ICFLoopSafetyInfo &SafetyInfo, ----
1501 MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU, ----
1502 ScalarEvolution *SE) { ----
1503 SafetyInfo.removeInstruction(&I); 0
1504 SafetyInfo.insertInstructionTo(&I, Dest.getParent()); 0
1505 I.moveBefore(&Dest); 0
1506 if (MemoryUseOrDef *OldMemAcc = cast_or_null( 0
1507 MSSAU.getMemorySSA()->getMemoryAccess(&I))) ----
1508 MSSAU.moveToPlace(OldMemAcc, Dest.getParent(), MemorySSA::BeforeTerminator); 0
1509 if (SE) 0
1510 SE->forgetBlockAndLoopDispositions(&I); 0
1511 } 0
1512 ----
1513 static Instruction *sinkThroughTriviallyReplaceablePHI( 0
1514 PHINode *TPN, Instruction *I, LoopInfo *LI, ----
1515 SmallDenseMap &SunkCopies, ----
1516 const LoopSafetyInfo *SafetyInfo, const Loop *CurLoop, ----
1517 MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU) { ----
1518 assert(isTriviallyReplaceablePHI(*TPN, *I) && 0
1519 "Expect only trivially replaceable PHI"); ----
1520 BasicBlock *ExitBlock = TPN->getParent(); 0
1521 Instruction *New; ----
1522 auto It = SunkCopies.find(ExitBlock); 0
1523 if (It != SunkCopies.end()) 0
1524 New = It->second; 0
1525 else ----
1526 New = SunkCopies[ExitBlock] = cloneInstructionInExitBlock( 0
1527 *I, *ExitBlock, *TPN, LI, SafetyInfo, MSSAU); ----
1528 return New; 0
1529 } ----
1530 ----
1531 static bool canSplitPredecessors(PHINode *PN, LoopSafetyInfo *SafetyInfo) { 0
1532 BasicBlock *BB = PN->getParent(); 0
1533 if (!BB->canSplitPredecessors()) 0
1534 return false; 0
1535 // It's not impossible to split EHPad blocks, but if BlockColors already exist ----
1536 // it require updating BlockColors for all offspring blocks accordingly. By ----
1537 // skipping such corner case, we can make updating BlockColors after splitting ----
1538 // predecessor fairly simple. ----
1539 if (!SafetyInfo->getBlockColors().empty() && BB->getFirstNonPHI()->isEHPad()) 0
1540 return false; 0
1541 for (BasicBlock *BBPred : predecessors(BB)) { 0
1542 if (isa(BBPred->getTerminator())) 0
1543 return false; 0
1544 } ----
1545 return true; 0
1546 } ----
1547 ----
1548 static void splitPredecessorsOfLoopExit(PHINode *PN, DominatorTree *DT, 0
1549 LoopInfo *LI, const Loop *CurLoop, ----
1550 LoopSafetyInfo *SafetyInfo, ----
1551 MemorySSAUpdater *MSSAU) { ----
1552 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
1553 SmallVector ExitBlocks; 0
1554 CurLoop->getUniqueExitBlocks(ExitBlocks); 0
1555 SmallPtrSet ExitBlockSet(ExitBlocks.begin(), ----
1556 ExitBlocks.end()); 0
1557 #endif ----
1558 BasicBlock *ExitBB = PN->getParent(); 0
1559 assert(ExitBlockSet.count(ExitBB) && "Expect the PHI is in an exit block."); 0
1560 ----
1561 // Split predecessors of the loop exit to make instructions in the loop are ----
1562 // exposed to exit blocks through trivially replaceable PHIs while keeping the ----
1563 // loop in the canonical form where each predecessor of each exit block should ----
1564 // be contained within the loop. For example, this will convert the loop below ----
1565 // from ----
1566 // ----
1567 // LB1: ----
1568 // %v1 = ----
1569 // br %LE, %LB2 ----
1570 // LB2: ----
1571 // %v2 = ----
1572 // br %LE, %LB1 ----
1573 // LE: ----
1574 // %p = phi [%v1, %LB1], [%v2, %LB2] <-- non-trivially replaceable ----
1575 // ----
1576 // to ----
1577 // ----
1578 // LB1: ----
1579 // %v1 = ----
1580 // br %LE.split, %LB2 ----
1581 // LB2: ----
1582 // %v2 = ----
1583 // br %LE.split2, %LB1 ----
1584 // LE.split: ----
1585 // %p1 = phi [%v1, %LB1] <-- trivially replaceable ----
1586 // br %LE ----
1587 // LE.split2: ----
1588 // %p2 = phi [%v2, %LB2] <-- trivially replaceable ----
1589 // br %LE ----
1590 // LE: ----
1591 // %p = phi [%p1, %LE.split], [%p2, %LE.split2] ----
1592 // ----
1593 const auto &BlockColors = SafetyInfo->getBlockColors(); 0
1594 SmallSetVector PredBBs(pred_begin(ExitBB), pred_end(ExitBB)); 0
1595 while (!PredBBs.empty()) { 0
1596 BasicBlock *PredBB = *PredBBs.begin(); 0
1597 assert(CurLoop->contains(PredBB) && 0
1598 "Expect all predecessors are in the loop"); ----
1599 if (PN->getBasicBlockIndex(PredBB) >= 0) { 0
1600 BasicBlock *NewPred = SplitBlockPredecessors( 0
1601 ExitBB, PredBB, ".split.loop.exit", DT, LI, MSSAU, true); ----
1602 // Since we do not allow splitting EH-block with BlockColors in ----
1603 // canSplitPredecessors(), we can simply assign predecessor's color to ----
1604 // the new block. ----
1605 if (!BlockColors.empty()) 0
1606 // Grab a reference to the ColorVector to be inserted before getting the ----
1607 // reference to the vector we are copying because inserting the new ----
1608 // element in BlockColors might cause the map to be reallocated. ----
1609 SafetyInfo->copyColors(NewPred, PredBB); 0
1610 } ----
1611 PredBBs.remove(PredBB); 0
1612 } ----
1613 } 0
1614 ----
1615 /// When an instruction is found to only be used outside of the loop, this ----
1616 /// function moves it to the exit blocks and patches up SSA form as needed. ----
1617 /// This method is guaranteed to remove the original instruction from its ----
1618 /// position, and may either delete it or move it to outside of the loop. ----
1619 /// ----
1620 static bool sink(Instruction &I, LoopInfo *LI, DominatorTree *DT, 0
1621 const Loop *CurLoop, ICFLoopSafetyInfo *SafetyInfo, ----
1622 MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU, OptimizationRemarkEmitter *ORE) { ----
1623 bool Changed = false; 0
1624 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "LICM sinking instruction: " << I << "\n"); 0
1625 ----
1626 // Iterate over users to be ready for actual sinking. Replace users via ----
1627 // unreachable blocks with undef and make all user PHIs trivially replaceable. ----
1628 SmallPtrSet VisitedUsers; 0
1629 for (Value::user_iterator UI = I.user_begin(), UE = I.user_end(); UI != UE;) { 0
1630 auto *User = cast(*UI); 0
1631 Use &U = UI.getUse(); 0
1632 ++UI; 0
1633 ----
1634 if (VisitedUsers.count(User) || CurLoop->contains(User)) 0
1635 continue; 0
1636 ----
1637 if (!DT->isReachableFromEntry(User->getParent())) { 0
1638 U = PoisonValue::get(I.getType()); 0
1639 Changed = true; 0
1640 continue; 0
1641 } ----
1642 ----
1643 // The user must be a PHI node. ----
1644 PHINode *PN = cast(User); 0
1645 ----
1646 // Surprisingly, instructions can be used outside of loops without any ----
1647 // exits. This can only happen in PHI nodes if the incoming block is ----
1648 // unreachable. ----
1649 BasicBlock *BB = PN->getIncomingBlock(U); 0
1650 if (!DT->isReachableFromEntry(BB)) { 0
1651 U = PoisonValue::get(I.getType()); 0
1652 Changed = true; 0
1653 continue; 0
1654 } ----
1655 ----
1656 VisitedUsers.insert(PN); 0
1657 if (isTriviallyReplaceablePHI(*PN, I)) 0
1658 continue; 0
1659 ----
1660 if (!canSplitPredecessors(PN, SafetyInfo)) 0
1661 return Changed; 0
1662 ----
1663 // Split predecessors of the PHI so that we can make users trivially ----
1664 // replaceable. ----
1665 splitPredecessorsOfLoopExit(PN, DT, LI, CurLoop, SafetyInfo, &MSSAU); 0
1666 ----
1667 // Should rebuild the iterators, as they may be invalidated by ----
1668 // splitPredecessorsOfLoopExit(). ----
1669 UI = I.user_begin(); 0
1670 UE = I.user_end(); 0
1671 } ----
1672 ----
1673 if (VisitedUsers.empty()) 0
1674 return Changed; 0
1675 ----
1676 ORE->emit([&]() { 0
1677 return OptimizationRemark(DEBUG_TYPE, "InstSunk", &I) 0
1678 << "sinking " << ore::NV("Inst", &I); 0
1679 }); ----
1680 if (isa(I)) 0
1681 ++NumMovedLoads; 0
1682 else if (isa(I)) 0
1683 ++NumMovedCalls; 0
1684 ++NumSunk; 0
1685 ----
1686 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
1687 SmallVector ExitBlocks; 0
1688 CurLoop->getUniqueExitBlocks(ExitBlocks); 0
1689 SmallPtrSet ExitBlockSet(ExitBlocks.begin(), ----
1690 ExitBlocks.end()); 0
1691 #endif ----
1692 ----
1693 // Clones of this instruction. Don't create more than one per exit block! ----
1694 SmallDenseMap SunkCopies; 0
1695 ----
1696 // If this instruction is only used outside of the loop, then all users are ----
1697 // PHI nodes in exit blocks due to LCSSA form. Just RAUW them with clones of ----
1698 // the instruction. ----
1699 // First check if I is worth sinking for all uses. Sink only when it is worth ----
1700 // across all uses. ----
1701 SmallSetVector Users(I.user_begin(), I.user_end()); 0
1702 for (auto *UI : Users) { 0
1703 auto *User = cast(UI); 0
1704 ----
1705 if (CurLoop->contains(User)) 0
1706 continue; 0
1707 ----
1708 PHINode *PN = cast(User); 0
1709 assert(ExitBlockSet.count(PN->getParent()) && 0
1710 "The LCSSA PHI is not in an exit block!"); ----
1711 ----
1712 // The PHI must be trivially replaceable. ----
1713 Instruction *New = sinkThroughTriviallyReplaceablePHI( 0
1714 PN, &I, LI, SunkCopies, SafetyInfo, CurLoop, MSSAU); ----
1715 // As we sink the instruction out of the BB, drop its debug location. ----
1716 New->dropLocation(); 0
1717 PN->replaceAllUsesWith(New); 0
1718 eraseInstruction(*PN, *SafetyInfo, MSSAU); 0
1719 Changed = true; 0
1720 } ----
1721 return Changed; 0
1722 } 0
1723 ----
1724 /// When an instruction is found to only use loop invariant operands that ----
1725 /// is safe to hoist, this instruction is called to do the dirty work. ----
1726 /// ----
1727 static void hoist(Instruction &I, const DominatorTree *DT, const Loop *CurLoop, 0
1728 BasicBlock *Dest, ICFLoopSafetyInfo *SafetyInfo, ----
1729 MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU, ScalarEvolution *SE, ----
1730 OptimizationRemarkEmitter *ORE) { ----
1731 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "LICM hoisting to " << Dest->getNameOrAsOperand() << ": " 0
1732 << I << "\n"); ----
1733 ORE->emit([&]() { 0
1734 return OptimizationRemark(DEBUG_TYPE, "Hoisted", &I) << "hoisting " 0
1735 << ore::NV("Inst", &I); 0
1736 }); ----
1737 ----
1738 // Metadata can be dependent on conditions we are hoisting above. ----
1739 // Conservatively strip all metadata on the instruction unless we were ----
1740 // guaranteed to execute I if we entered the loop, in which case the metadata ----
1741 // is valid in the loop preheader. ----
1742 // Similarly, If I is a call and it is not guaranteed to execute in the loop, ----
1743 // then moving to the preheader means we should strip attributes on the call ----
1744 // that can cause UB since we may be hoisting above conditions that allowed ----
1745 // inferring those attributes. They may not be valid at the preheader. ----
1746 if ((I.hasMetadataOtherThanDebugLoc() || isa(I)) && 0
1747 // The check on hasMetadataOtherThanDebugLoc is to prevent us from burning ----
1748 // time in isGuaranteedToExecute if we don't actually have anything to ----
1749 // drop. It is a compile time optimization, not required for correctness. ----
1750 !SafetyInfo->isGuaranteedToExecute(I, DT, CurLoop)) 0
1751 I.dropUBImplyingAttrsAndMetadata(); 0
1752 ----
1753 if (isa(I)) 0
1754 // Move the new node to the end of the phi list in the destination block. ----
1755 moveInstructionBefore(I, *Dest->getFirstNonPHI(), *SafetyInfo, MSSAU, SE); 0
1756 else ----
1757 // Move the new node to the destination block, before its terminator. ----
1758 moveInstructionBefore(I, *Dest->getTerminator(), *SafetyInfo, MSSAU, SE); 0
1759 ----
1760 I.updateLocationAfterHoist(); 0
1761 ----
1762 if (isa(I)) 0
1763 ++NumMovedLoads; 0
1764 else if (isa(I)) 0
1765 ++NumMovedCalls; 0
1766 ++NumHoisted; 0
1767 } 0
1768 ----
1769 /// Only sink or hoist an instruction if it is not a trapping instruction, ----
1770 /// or if the instruction is known not to trap when moved to the preheader. ----
1771 /// or if it is a trapping instruction and is guaranteed to execute. ----
1772 static bool isSafeToExecuteUnconditionally( 0
1773 Instruction &Inst, const DominatorTree *DT, const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI, ----
1774 const Loop *CurLoop, const LoopSafetyInfo *SafetyInfo, ----
1775 OptimizationRemarkEmitter *ORE, const Instruction *CtxI, ----
1776 AssumptionCache *AC, bool AllowSpeculation) { ----
1777 if (AllowSpeculation && 0
1778 isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(&Inst, CtxI, AC, DT, TLI)) 0
1779 return true; 0
1780 ----
1781 bool GuaranteedToExecute = ----
1782 SafetyInfo->isGuaranteedToExecute(Inst, DT, CurLoop); 0
1783 ----
1784 if (!GuaranteedToExecute) { 0
1785 auto *LI = dyn_cast(&Inst); 0
1786 if (LI && CurLoop->isLoopInvariant(LI->getPointerOperand())) 0
1787 ORE->emit([&]() { 0
1788 return OptimizationRemarkMissed( 0
1789 DEBUG_TYPE, "LoadWithLoopInvariantAddressCondExecuted", LI) 0
1790 << "failed to hoist load with loop-invariant address " ----
1791 "because load is conditionally executed"; 0
1792 }); ----
1793 } ----
1794 ----
1795 return GuaranteedToExecute; 0
1796 } ----
1797 ----
1798 namespace { ----
1799 class LoopPromoter : public LoadAndStorePromoter { ----
1800 Value *SomePtr; // Designated pointer to store to. ----
1801 SmallVectorImpl &LoopExitBlocks; ----
1802 SmallVectorImpl &LoopInsertPts; ----
1803 SmallVectorImpl &MSSAInsertPts; ----
1804 PredIteratorCache &PredCache; ----
1805 MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU; ----
1806 LoopInfo &LI; ----
1807 DebugLoc DL; ----
1808 Align Alignment; ----
1809 bool UnorderedAtomic; ----
1810 AAMDNodes AATags; ----
1811 ICFLoopSafetyInfo &SafetyInfo; ----
1812 bool CanInsertStoresInExitBlocks; ----
1813 ArrayRef Uses; ----
1814 ----
1815 // We're about to add a use of V in a loop exit block. Insert an LCSSA phi ----
1816 // (if legal) if doing so would add an out-of-loop use to an instruction ----
1817 // defined in-loop. ----
1818 Value *maybeInsertLCSSAPHI(Value *V, BasicBlock *BB) const { 0
1819 if (!LI.wouldBeOutOfLoopUseRequiringLCSSA(V, BB)) 0
1820 return V; 0
1821 ----
1822 Instruction *I = cast(V); 0
1823 // We need to create an LCSSA PHI node for the incoming value and ----
1824 // store that. ----
1825 PHINode *PN = PHINode::Create(I->getType(), PredCache.size(BB), 0
1826 I->getName() + ".lcssa", &BB->front()); 0
1827 for (BasicBlock *Pred : PredCache.get(BB)) 0
1828 PN->addIncoming(I, Pred); 0
1829 return PN; 0
1830 } ----
1831 ----
1832 public: ----
1833 LoopPromoter(Value *SP, ArrayRef Insts, SSAUpdater &S, 0
1834 SmallVectorImpl &LEB, ----
1835 SmallVectorImpl &LIP, ----
1836 SmallVectorImpl &MSSAIP, PredIteratorCache &PIC, ----
1837 MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU, LoopInfo &li, DebugLoc dl, ----
1838 Align Alignment, bool UnorderedAtomic, const AAMDNodes &AATags, ----
1839 ICFLoopSafetyInfo &SafetyInfo, bool CanInsertStoresInExitBlocks) ----
1840 : LoadAndStorePromoter(Insts, S), SomePtr(SP), LoopExitBlocks(LEB), 0
1841 LoopInsertPts(LIP), MSSAInsertPts(MSSAIP), PredCache(PIC), MSSAU(MSSAU), 0
1842 LI(li), DL(std::move(dl)), Alignment(Alignment), 0
1843 UnorderedAtomic(UnorderedAtomic), AATags(AATags), 0
1844 SafetyInfo(SafetyInfo), 0
1845 CanInsertStoresInExitBlocks(CanInsertStoresInExitBlocks), Uses(Insts) {} 0
1846 ----
1847 void insertStoresInLoopExitBlocks() { 0
1848 // Insert stores after in the loop exit blocks. Each exit block gets a ----
1849 // store of the live-out values that feed them. Since we've already told ----
1850 // the SSA updater about the defs in the loop and the preheader ----
1851 // definition, it is all set and we can start using it. ----
1852 DIAssignID *NewID = nullptr; 0
1853 for (unsigned i = 0, e = LoopExitBlocks.size(); i != e; ++i) { 0
1854 BasicBlock *ExitBlock = LoopExitBlocks[i]; 0
1855 Value *LiveInValue = SSA.GetValueInMiddleOfBlock(ExitBlock); 0
1856 LiveInValue = maybeInsertLCSSAPHI(LiveInValue, ExitBlock); 0
1857 Value *Ptr = maybeInsertLCSSAPHI(SomePtr, ExitBlock); 0
1858 Instruction *InsertPos = LoopInsertPts[i]; 0
1859 StoreInst *NewSI = new StoreInst(LiveInValue, Ptr, InsertPos); 0
1860 if (UnorderedAtomic) 0
1861 NewSI->setOrdering(AtomicOrdering::Unordered); 0
1862 NewSI->setAlignment(Alignment); 0
1863 NewSI->setDebugLoc(DL); 0
1864 // Attach DIAssignID metadata to the new store, generating it on the ----
1865 // first loop iteration. ----
1866 if (i == 0) { 0
1867 // NewSI will have its DIAssignID set here if there are any stores in ----
1868 // Uses with a DIAssignID attachment. This merged ID will then be ----
1869 // attached to the other inserted stores (in the branch below). ----
1870 NewSI->mergeDIAssignID(Uses); 0
1871 NewID = cast_or_null( 0
1872 NewSI->getMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_DIAssignID)); ----
1873 } else { ----
1874 // Attach the DIAssignID (or nullptr) merged from Uses in the branch ----
1875 // above. ----
1876 NewSI->setMetadata(LLVMContext::MD_DIAssignID, NewID); 0
1877 } ----
1878 ----
1879 if (AATags) 0
1880 NewSI->setAAMetadata(AATags); 0
1881 ----
1882 MemoryAccess *MSSAInsertPoint = MSSAInsertPts[i]; 0
1883 MemoryAccess *NewMemAcc; ----
1884 if (!MSSAInsertPoint) { 0
1885 NewMemAcc = MSSAU.createMemoryAccessInBB( 0
1886 NewSI, nullptr, NewSI->getParent(), MemorySSA::Beginning); 0
1887 } else { ----
1888 NewMemAcc = ----
1889 MSSAU.createMemoryAccessAfter(NewSI, nullptr, MSSAInsertPoint); 0
1890 } ----
1891 MSSAInsertPts[i] = NewMemAcc; 0
1892 MSSAU.insertDef(cast(NewMemAcc), true); 0
1893 // FIXME: true for safety, false may still be correct. ----
1894 } ----
1895 } 0
1896 ----
1897 void doExtraRewritesBeforeFinalDeletion() override { 0
1898 if (CanInsertStoresInExitBlocks) 0
1899 insertStoresInLoopExitBlocks(); 0
1900 } 0
1901 ----
1902 void instructionDeleted(Instruction *I) const override { 0
1903 SafetyInfo.removeInstruction(I); 0
1904 MSSAU.removeMemoryAccess(I); 0
1905 } 0
1906 ----
1907 bool shouldDelete(Instruction *I) const override { 0
1908 if (isa(I)) 0
1909 return CanInsertStoresInExitBlocks; 0
1910 return true; 0
1911 } ----
1912 }; ----
1913 ----
1914 bool isNotCapturedBeforeOrInLoop(const Value *V, const Loop *L, 0
1915 DominatorTree *DT) { ----
1916 // We can perform the captured-before check against any instruction in the ----
1917 // loop header, as the loop header is reachable from any instruction inside ----
1918 // the loop. ----
1919 // TODO: ReturnCaptures=true shouldn't be necessary here. ----
1920 return !PointerMayBeCapturedBefore(V, /* ReturnCaptures */ true, 0
1921 /* StoreCaptures */ true, ----
1922 L->getHeader()->getTerminator(), DT); 0
1923 } ----
1924 ----
1925 /// Return true if we can prove that a caller cannot inspect the object if an ----
1926 /// unwind occurs inside the loop. ----
1927 bool isNotVisibleOnUnwindInLoop(const Value *Object, const Loop *L, 0
1928 DominatorTree *DT) { ----
1929 bool RequiresNoCaptureBeforeUnwind; ----
1930 if (!isNotVisibleOnUnwind(Object, RequiresNoCaptureBeforeUnwind)) 0
1931 return false; 0
1932 ----
1933 return !RequiresNoCaptureBeforeUnwind || 0
1934 isNotCapturedBeforeOrInLoop(Object, L, DT); 0
1935 } ----
1936 ----
1937 // We don't consider globals as writable: While the physical memory is writable, ----
1938 // we may not have provenance to perform the write. ----
1939 bool isWritableObject(const Value *Object) { 0
1940 // TODO: Alloca might not be writable after its lifetime ends. ----
1941 // See https://github.com/llvm/llvm-project/issues/51838. ----
1942 if (isa(Object)) 0
1943 return true; 0
1944 ----
1945 // TODO: Also handle sret. ----
1946 if (auto *A = dyn_cast(Object)) 0
1947 return A->hasByValAttr(); 0
1948 ----
1949 // TODO: Noalias has nothing to do with writability, this should check for ----
1950 // an allocator function. ----
1951 return isNoAliasCall(Object); 0
1952 } ----
1953 ----
1954 bool isThreadLocalObject(const Value *Object, const Loop *L, DominatorTree *DT, 0
1955 TargetTransformInfo *TTI) { ----
1956 // The object must be function-local to start with, and then not captured ----
1957 // before/in the loop. ----
1958 return (isIdentifiedFunctionLocal(Object) && 0
1959 isNotCapturedBeforeOrInLoop(Object, L, DT)) || 0
1960 (TTI->isSingleThreaded() || SingleThread); 0
1961 } ----
1962 ----
1963 } // namespace ----
1964 ----
1965 /// Try to promote memory values to scalars by sinking stores out of the ----
1966 /// loop and moving loads to before the loop. We do this by looping over ----
1967 /// the stores in the loop, looking for stores to Must pointers which are ----
1968 /// loop invariant. ----
1969 /// ----
1970 bool llvm::promoteLoopAccessesToScalars( 0
1971 const SmallSetVector &PointerMustAliases, ----
1972 SmallVectorImpl &ExitBlocks, ----
1973 SmallVectorImpl &InsertPts, ----
1974 SmallVectorImpl &MSSAInsertPts, PredIteratorCache &PIC, ----
1975 LoopInfo *LI, DominatorTree *DT, AssumptionCache *AC, ----
1976 const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI, TargetTransformInfo *TTI, Loop *CurLoop, ----
1977 MemorySSAUpdater &MSSAU, ICFLoopSafetyInfo *SafetyInfo, ----
1978 OptimizationRemarkEmitter *ORE, bool AllowSpeculation, ----
1979 bool HasReadsOutsideSet) { ----
1980 // Verify inputs. ----
1981 assert(LI != nullptr && DT != nullptr && CurLoop != nullptr && 0
1982 SafetyInfo != nullptr && ----
1983 "Unexpected Input to promoteLoopAccessesToScalars"); ----
1984 ----
1985 LLVM_DEBUG({ 0
1986 dbgs() << "Trying to promote set of must-aliased pointers:\n"; ----
1987 for (Value *Ptr : PointerMustAliases) ----
1988 dbgs() << " " << *Ptr << "\n"; ----
1989 }); ----
1990 ++NumPromotionCandidates; 0
1991 ----
1992 Value *SomePtr = *PointerMustAliases.begin(); 0
1993 BasicBlock *Preheader = CurLoop->getLoopPreheader(); 0
1994 ----
1995 // It is not safe to promote a load/store from the loop if the load/store is ----
1996 // conditional. For example, turning: ----
1997 // ----
1998 // for () { if (c) *P += 1; } ----
1999 // ----
2000 // into: ----
2001 // ----
2002 // tmp = *P; for () { if (c) tmp +=1; } *P = tmp; ----
2003 // ----
2004 // is not safe, because *P may only be valid to access if 'c' is true. ----
2005 // ----
2006 // The safety property divides into two parts: ----
2007 // p1) The memory may not be dereferenceable on entry to the loop. In this ----
2008 // case, we can't insert the required load in the preheader. ----
2009 // p2) The memory model does not allow us to insert a store along any dynamic ----
2010 // path which did not originally have one. ----
2011 // ----
2012 // If at least one store is guaranteed to execute, both properties are ----
2013 // satisfied, and promotion is legal. ----
2014 // ----
2015 // This, however, is not a necessary condition. Even if no store/load is ----
2016 // guaranteed to execute, we can still establish these properties. ----
2017 // We can establish (p1) by proving that hoisting the load into the preheader ----
2018 // is safe (i.e. proving dereferenceability on all paths through the loop). We ----
2019 // can use any access within the alias set to prove dereferenceability, ----
2020 // since they're all must alias. ----
2021 // ----
2022 // There are two ways establish (p2): ----
2023 // a) Prove the location is thread-local. In this case the memory model ----
2024 // requirement does not apply, and stores are safe to insert. ----
2025 // b) Prove a store dominates every exit block. In this case, if an exit ----
2026 // blocks is reached, the original dynamic path would have taken us through ----
2027 // the store, so inserting a store into the exit block is safe. Note that this ----
2028 // is different from the store being guaranteed to execute. For instance, ----
2029 // if an exception is thrown on the first iteration of the loop, the original ----
2030 // store is never executed, but the exit blocks are not executed either. ----
2031 ----
2032 bool DereferenceableInPH = false; 0
2033 bool StoreIsGuanteedToExecute = false; 0
2034 bool FoundLoadToPromote = false; 0
2035 // Goes from Unknown to either Safe or Unsafe, but can't switch between them. ----
2036 enum { ----
2037 StoreSafe, ----
2038 StoreUnsafe, ----
2039 StoreSafetyUnknown, ----
2040 } StoreSafety = StoreSafetyUnknown; 0
2041 ----
2042 SmallVector LoopUses; 0
2043 ----
2044 // We start with an alignment of one and try to find instructions that allow ----
2045 // us to prove better alignment. ----
2046 Align Alignment; 0
2047 // Keep track of which types of access we see ----
2048 bool SawUnorderedAtomic = false; 0
2049 bool SawNotAtomic = false; 0
2050 AAMDNodes AATags; 0
2051 ----
2052 const DataLayout &MDL = Preheader->getModule()->getDataLayout(); 0
2053 ----
2054 // If there are reads outside the promoted set, then promoting stores is ----
2055 // definitely not safe. ----
2056 if (HasReadsOutsideSet) 0
2057 StoreSafety = StoreUnsafe; 0
2058 ----
2059 if (StoreSafety == StoreSafetyUnknown && SafetyInfo->anyBlockMayThrow()) { 0
2060 // If a loop can throw, we have to insert a store along each unwind edge. ----
2061 // That said, we can't actually make the unwind edge explicit. Therefore, ----
2062 // we have to prove that the store is dead along the unwind edge. We do ----
2063 // this by proving that the caller can't have a reference to the object ----
2064 // after return and thus can't possibly load from the object. ----
2065 Value *Object = getUnderlyingObject(SomePtr); 0
2066 if (!isNotVisibleOnUnwindInLoop(Object, CurLoop, DT)) 0
2067 StoreSafety = StoreUnsafe; 0
2068 } ----
2069 ----
2070 // Check that all accesses to pointers in the alias set use the same type. ----
2071 // We cannot (yet) promote a memory location that is loaded and stored in ----
2072 // different sizes. While we are at it, collect alignment and AA info. ----
2073 Type *AccessTy = nullptr; 0
2074 for (Value *ASIV : PointerMustAliases) { 0
2075 for (Use &U : ASIV->uses()) { 0
2076 // Ignore instructions that are outside the loop. ----
2077 Instruction *UI = dyn_cast(U.getUser()); 0
2078 if (!UI || !CurLoop->contains(UI)) 0
2079 continue; 0
2080 ----
2081 // If there is an non-load/store instruction in the loop, we can't promote ----
2082 // it. ----
2083 if (LoadInst *Load = dyn_cast(UI)) { 0
2084 if (!Load->isUnordered()) 0
2085 return false; 0
2086 ----
2087 SawUnorderedAtomic |= Load->isAtomic(); 0
2088 SawNotAtomic |= !Load->isAtomic(); 0
2089 FoundLoadToPromote = true; 0
2090 ----
2091 Align InstAlignment = Load->getAlign(); 0
2092 ----
2093 // Note that proving a load safe to speculate requires proving ----
2094 // sufficient alignment at the target location. Proving it guaranteed ----
2095 // to execute does as well. Thus we can increase our guaranteed ----
2096 // alignment as well. ----
2097 if (!DereferenceableInPH || (InstAlignment > Alignment)) 0
2098 if (isSafeToExecuteUnconditionally( 0
2099 *Load, DT, TLI, CurLoop, SafetyInfo, ORE, ----
2100 Preheader->getTerminator(), AC, AllowSpeculation)) { 0
2101 DereferenceableInPH = true; 0
2102 Alignment = std::max(Alignment, InstAlignment); 0
2103 } ----
2104 } else if (const StoreInst *Store = dyn_cast(UI)) { 0
2105 // Stores *of* the pointer are not interesting, only stores *to* the ----
2106 // pointer. ----
2107 if (U.getOperandNo() != StoreInst::getPointerOperandIndex()) 0
2108 continue; 0
2109 if (!Store->isUnordered()) 0
2110 return false; 0
2111 ----
2112 SawUnorderedAtomic |= Store->isAtomic(); 0
2113 SawNotAtomic |= !Store->isAtomic(); 0
2114 ----
2115 // If the store is guaranteed to execute, both properties are satisfied. ----
2116 // We may want to check if a store is guaranteed to execute even if we ----
2117 // already know that promotion is safe, since it may have higher ----
